# Hyper keep-alive via tableauhyperapi, held resident by lib/repl-engine.py.
# Vanilla hyper-parquet spawns a fresh HyperProcess and re-runs create.sql on
# EVERY query (both outside the timed region); here one HyperProcess +
# Connection persists for the whole run. Timing is perf_counter around
# execute_list_query, exactly as the vanilla script times it.
#
# We predicted this would be the inert control: Hyper's per-call HyperProcess +
# create.sql tax sits OUTSIDE the timed region, so keeping it alive "shouldn't"
# help the recorded number. Empirically it moved the MOST (~2.17x geomean,
# faster on all 43 queries, last place -> 3rd). The prediction was incomplete:
# the timed execute_list_query ITSELF carries first-query costs in a fresh
# process (query compilation, cold buffer pool, parquet metadata warmup) that
# vanish when the process persists. A good reminder for the post — the engine I
# was surest about was the one I got most wrong.

REPL_NAME="hyper (python)"
REPL_CMD="myenv/bin/python3 ../lib/repl-engine.py hyper"
REPL_INIT_CMDS=""
REPL_SENTINEL_EMIT=".print %s"
REPL_PROBE_SQL="SELECT 1;"
REPL_QUIT=".quit"

repl_parse_timing() { awk '/^Run Time/ { print $5 }'; }
repl_result_filter() { grep -v '^Run Time ' | grep -v '^CBDONE_'; }
